To find the rank of the matrix A, we need to perform Gaussian elimination to find the row echelon form of the matrix and then count the number of non-zero rows.

Matrix A:

\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 2 & 3 \\
4 & 5 & 6 \\
7 & 8 & 9 \\
\end{bmatrix}

Step 1: Subtract 4 times the first row from the second row, and subtract 7 times the first row from the third row.

\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 2 & 3 \\
0 & -3 & -6 \\
0 & -6 & -12 \\
\end{bmatrix}

Step 2: Divide the second row by -3.

\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 2 & 3 \\
0 & 1 & 2 \\
0 & -6 & -12 \\
\end{bmatrix}

Step 3: Add 6 times the second row to the third row.

\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 2 & 3 \\
0 & 1 & 2 \\
0 & 0 & 0 \\
\end{bmatrix}

Now the matrix is in row echelon form. There are 2 non-zero rows, so the rank of the matrix A is 2.
